<section class="section" id="strength">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-bar bar-red"></div>
      <h2>Muscular Strength Assessments</h2>
    </div>

    <figure style="margin:2rem 0;text-align:center;"><img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1690731033723-ad718c6e585a?fm=jpg&q=80&w=1400&auto=format&fit=max&ixlib=rb-4.1.0" alt="Client performing bench press — 1-RM strength assessment with proper form and spotter" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;border-radius:10px;" loading="lazy"><figcaption style="margin-top:8px;font-size:0.85rem;color:#94a3b8;">1-RM bench press: the gold standard for upper-body push strength assessment. Photo: Unsplash (Free to use)</figcaption></figure>

    <p>Muscular strength is the maximum amount of force a muscle or group of muscles can produce against an external resistance in a single effort. It is foundational to everything from picking up grocery bags to preventing falls to competitive athletic performance. Unlike muscular endurance, strength is about peak force — and assessing it requires careful attention to safety, technique, and client readiness.</p>

    <h3>Absolute vs. Relative Strength</h3>
    <p>Absolute strength is the total amount of weight lifted — the raw number. Relative strength accounts for the client's body weight, making it the more useful metric for comparing individuals or tracking meaningful progress over time.</p>

    <div class="callout callout-blue">
      <div class="callout-label">Formula — Relative Strength</div>
      <p><strong>Relative Strength = Absolute Strength ÷ Body Weight</strong><br><br>
      Example: A client who bench presses 205 lb and weighs 175 lb has a relative strength of 1.17 (205 ÷ 175). This is the figure compared against normative data tables.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout callout-red">
      <div class="callout-label">Warning — 1-RM Contraindications</div>
      <p>Maximal exertion assessments like the 1-RM bench press and squat are <strong>not appropriate</strong> for most beginners as a starting baseline. Clients with hypertension or a history of vascular disease should avoid 1-RM assessments entirely. These tests require demonstrated proficiency in the movement pattern — never administer a 1-RM assessment to a client who is not already comfortable with free-weight technique. Avoid the Valsalva maneuver (breath-holding) in all strength assessments.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>The 1-RM Bench Press Assessment</h3>
    <p>The 1-RM bench press evaluates upper-extremity pushing strength using one of the most universally recognized movement patterns in strength training. It is suitable only for clients who can demonstrate proper bench press form and have no history of shoulder problems.</p>

    <h4>Technique Requirements</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Client lies supine, eyes below the racked bar, head and shoulders and buttocks firmly on the bench.</li>
      <li>Feet flat on the floor (or on a riser for clients with lower-back concerns).</li>
      <li>Closed pronated grip, hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart.</li>
      <li>Full ROM: arms fully extended at the top; bar lightly touches the chest (mid-sternum) at the bottom.</li>
      <li>Inhale on the descent, exhale during the press. No breath-holding.</li>
      <li>Elbows should not lock out; do not bounce the bar off the chest.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Progressive Protocol</h4>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>Warm-up set</strong>Light resistance, 5–10 reps. Rest 1 minute. Establishes the movement pattern and provides information for load selection.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>Second set</strong>Based on warm-up, select a load for 3–5 reps. Rest 2 minutes. Increase by approximately 5–10% from here.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>Third set</strong>One heavy set of 2–3 reps. Rest 2–4 minutes. Use the 1-RM prediction table to determine next workload.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">4</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>1-RM attempt</strong>If successful, rest 2–4 minutes and attempt a heavier load. If unsuccessful, reduce by 5–10% and retry. Ideally the true 1-RM is found within 3–5 total testing sets.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Percentile</th><th>Rating</th><th>Men 20–29</th><th>Men 30–39</th><th>Men 40–49</th><th>Men 50–59</th><th>Men 60+</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>95</td><td style="color:var(--blue)">Superior</td><td>1.76</td><td>1.63</td><td>1.35</td><td>1.20</td><td>1.05</td></tr>
          <tr><td>80</td><td style="color:var(--green)">Excellent</td><td>1.34</td><td>1.32</td><td>1.12</td><td>1.00</td><td>0.90</td></tr>
          <tr><td>60</td><td style="color:var(--gold)">Good</td><td>1.19</td><td>1.14</td><td>0.98</td><td>0.88</td><td>0.79</td></tr>
          <tr><td>40</td><td>Fair</td><td>1.06</td><td>0.99</td><td>0.88</td><td>0.80</td><td>0.71</td></tr>
          <tr><td>20</td><td>Poor</td><td>0.89</td><td>0.88</td><td>0.78</td><td>0.72</td><td>0.63</td></tr>
          <tr><td>5</td><td style="color:var(--red)">Very Poor</td><td>0.76</td><td>0.72</td><td>0.65</td><td>0.59</td><td>0.53</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><em>Values shown as ratio of bench press weight to body weight. Source: The Cooper Institute.</em></p>

    <h3>The 1-RM Squat Assessment</h3>
    <p>The squat is the definitive lower-body strength assessment. It is suitable only for clients who demonstrate proper squat form and are free from low-back or knee pain. The loading protocol mirrors the bench press approach: progressive sets building to a true one-repetition maximum, ideally achieved within 3–5 testing sets.</p>

    <h4>Key Technical Points</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Bar positioned in high-bar (on upper trapezius) or low-bar (across posterior deltoids) position.</li>
      <li>Feet shoulder-width apart, flat on the floor throughout.</li>
      <li>Descent initiated by hinging at the hips before bending the knees — the hip-hinge initiation protects the ACL.</li>
      <li>ROM: standing to thighs parallel to the floor (or slightly below parallel if the client demonstrates appropriate mobility).</li>
      <li>Inhale on the descent, exhale during the ascent. Drive through the heels on the way up.</li>
      <li>Workload increases of 10–20% per set, starting from a 5-rep warm-up.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Submaximal Strength Assessments</h3>
    <p>When a true 1-RM is not appropriate — either because the client is inexperienced, health concerns exist, or the session context doesn't support maximal testing — submaximal assessments using 10 or fewer repetitions are a valid and safer alternative. The predicted 1-RM is calculated from the repetitions completed and the load used.</p>

    <div class="callout callout-blue">
      <div class="callout-label">Key Concept — Predicting 1-RM from Submaximal Effort</div>
      <p>Use the 1-RM Prediction Coefficient Table: multiply the weight lifted by the coefficient for the number of reps completed. Example: A client completes 8 bench press repetitions at 160 lb. The coefficient for 8 reps is 1.255. Predicted 1-RM = 160 × 1.255 = <strong>201 lb (91 kg)</strong>. This approach is safer and more appropriate for most everyday fitness clients than a true maximal effort.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Reps Completed</th>
            <th>Squat/Leg Press Coefficient</th>
            <th>Bench/Upper-body Coefficient</th>
            <th>% of 1-RM</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1</td><td>1.000</td><td>1.000</td><td>100%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2</td><td>1.0475</td><td>1.035</td><td>97%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>4</td><td>1.1375</td><td>1.115</td><td>90%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>6</td><td>1.242</td><td>1.185</td><td>85%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>8</td><td>1.326</td><td>1.255</td><td>80%</td></tr>
          <tr><td>10</td><td>1.41</td><td>1.325</td><td>75%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Muscle Balance and Strength Ratios</h3>
    <p>Strength assessments are also used to evaluate the balance between opposing muscle groups — agonist-to-antagonist ratios. Chronic imbalances from overuse, side dominance, or poor program design create injury risk and movement dysfunction. These recommended ratios serve as programming targets:</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Joint</th><th>Movement Pairing</th><th>Target Ratio</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Shoulder</td><td>Anterior deltoid : Posterior deltoid/trapezius</td><td>2:3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Shoulder</td><td>Internal rotation : External rotation</td><td>3:2</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Elbow</td><td>Flexion : Extension (biceps : triceps)</td><td>1:1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lumbar spine</td><td>Flexion : Extension</td><td>1:1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Hip</td><td>Flexion : Extension</td><td>1:1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Knee</td><td>Flexion : Extension (hamstrings : quadriceps)</td><td>2:3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Ankle</td><td>Plantar flexion : Dorsiflexion</td><td>3:1</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Ankle</td><td>Inversion : Eversion</td><td>1:1</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Spotting: The Non-Negotiable Safety Standard</h3>
    <p>Every free-weight strength assessment involving barbells or dumbbells requires proper spotting. A personal trainer alone may not be sufficient — a second spotter is recommended for 1-RM attempts with bench press and squat. Key spotting principles:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The spotter must have the leverage and strength to safely handle the load being tested.</li>
      <li>For over-the-face exercises (bench press), use an alternated (mixed) grip — overhand and underhand — with hands between the client's hands.</li>
      <li>Spot as close to the dumbbell as possible for dumbbell exercises.</li>
      <li>All overhead or loaded bar exercises should be performed within a power rack when available.</li>
      <li>During 1-RM assessments, the spotter should anticipate taking the bar immediately if the client fails — don't wait for collapse.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

