<!-- SECTION 9: POWER & SPEED ASSESSMENTS        -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="power">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-bar bar-green"></div>
      <h2>Power and Speed, Agility, and Quickness Assessments</h2>
    </div>

    <p>Power is not simply strength applied quickly — it is defined as the rate at which mechanical work is performed: <strong>Power = Force × Distance ÷ Time</strong>, or equivalently <strong>Power = Force × Velocity</strong>. It represents the immediate energy available through the anaerobic (phosphagen) energy system. Athletic performance in virtually every sport depends on power: a vertical jump in basketball, an explosive first step in soccer, a golf swing, or a sprint off the starting blocks.</p>

    <p>Power and strength are closely related, but should be assessed independently — a strong athlete is not necessarily powerful, and training programs need to address both qualities separately. Power assessments are most relevant to clients in the Load/Speed Training phase, and most normative data has been collected from collegiate and professional athlete populations.</p>

    <div class="callout callout-red">
      <div class="callout-label">Warning — Contraindications for Power and Speed Tests</div>
      <p>Power, speed, agility, and quickness assessments are intended for athletes and those in advanced training phases. Clients with orthopedic limitations or those recovering from injury are not appropriate candidates. A proper warm-up — minimum 5–10 minutes of light cardiorespiratory activity, short sprints, and dynamic lower-body stretching — is mandatory before any power or speed testing.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Vertical Jump Assessment</h3>
    <p>The vertical jump is the simplest, most widely used measure of lower-body explosive power. It requires nothing more than a smooth wall, chalk, a flat non-slip surface, a measuring tape, and a small step stool. Despite its simplicity, it correlates significantly with overall athletic power output and is a standard component of performance testing in basketball, volleyball, football, and many other sports.</p>

    <h4>Protocol</h4>
    <div class="steps">
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>Standing reach height</strong>Standing flat-footed, the client raises the inside arm overhead as high as possible. Mark the wall with chalk. This is the baseline height.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>Jump</strong>The client lowers the arms, drops into a quarter-squat without any pause, and explosively jumps as high as possible — using full arm and leg propulsion. At peak height, they mark the wall with chalk.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-body"><strong>Measurement</strong>The vertical jump score is the vertical distance between the standing reach mark and the jump mark. Administer three trials; record the maximum height achieved.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Category</th>
            <th>Men 20–29 (cm)</th>
            <th>Men 30–39 (cm)</th>
