<!-- TAKEAWAYS                                    -->
<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="takeaways">
  <h2>Chapter 10 Key Takeaways</h2>
  <p class="sub">The essential principles every trainer needs to assess, interpret, and program effectively</p>
  <div class="takeaway-grid">
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">01</div>
      <h3>Assessments Are Client-Centered, Not Protocol-Driven</h3>
      <p>The client's goals, comfort level, and readiness determine which assessments are appropriate — not a fixed checklist. Use the ACE Mover Method to guide selection: ask, listen, and adapt.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">02</div>
      <h3>Static Posture Reveals Dynamic Compensations</h3>
      <p>Poor resting posture predicts poor movement patterns. Identify the five major deviations — pronation, hip adduction, pelvic tilt, shoulder protraction, forward head — and trace them to their underlying muscle imbalances.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">03</div>
      <h3>Core Endurance Ratios Matter More Than Raw Times</h3>
      <p>McGill's battery is interpreted through three ratios: flexion:extension (under 1.0), right:left side-bridge (within 0.05 of 1.0), and side-bridge:extension (under 0.75). Imbalance predicts low-back dysfunction.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">04</div>
      <h3>Movement Screens Require Uncoached Observation</h3>
      <p>Never cue technique during a movement assessment. The value of these screens is observing the client's natural, unmodified movement patterns — compensations disappear the moment you tell someone what to fix.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">05</div>
      <h3>1-RM Testing Is Not for Most Beginners</h3>
      <p>True maximal strength assessments require demonstrated technique proficiency and are contraindicated for clients with hypertension, vascular disease, or orthopedic concerns. Submaximal prediction is safer and often more practical.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">06</div>
      <h3>Reassess Regularly to Document Progress</h3>
      <p>Assessments are an ongoing tool, not a one-time intake event. Link reassessment milestones to SMART goals agreed upon with the client, and use follow-up data to adjust programming and sustain motivation.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">07</div>
      <h3>Communicate Results in the Client's Language</h3>
      <p>Lead with positives. Connect technical findings to the client's personal goals. Explain the "why" behind corrective exercise recommendations. Make data meaningful, not intimidating.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="takeaway-card">
      <div class="takeaway-num">08</div>
      <h3>Sequence Assessments to Protect Validity</h3>
      <p>Postural and flexibility work before movement screening, movement screening before endurance testing, endurance before strength, strength before power. Fatigue from earlier tests corrupts later results if order is ignored.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

